      "writtenOn": "2019-08-16T21:15:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This becomes hard to use. The public API is Write() and Flush(). If a consumer has some data they need to push through this class, they’ll essentially allocate a ZlibOutputStream, do whatever it takes to Write(), and then call Flush(). But assume that they Write() chunks of data in a loop. If there’s no data to write at all, they’ll never call Write(). This should not be an error. The subsequent Flush() will trip this DCHECK.\n\nOverall, I’d say that your entire use of initialized_ is a bit freaky. Usually we consider “initialization” to be something that an external user would direct. Here, it’s more of a nonstandard implementation detail. Under that regime, it needs to be entirely transparent to the user.\n\nIn fact, what I’d suggest is that nothing about your Initialize() really needs to be broken out as something independent of the constructor at all. I’d move all of that initialization stuff into the constructor, which will simplify things considerably because initialized_ won’t need to exist and be checked at all. That’d resolve the complex interactions between initialized_ and flushed_. However, see below about the potential for Initialize() to fail. I’ll continue the discussion there.",
      "revId": "7438e06f309a431d675c1b81e75fc31071f20d2b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2f2b2fe7_f4752d9d",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream.cc",
