    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d5dbdda5_82f51099",
        "filename": "util/stream/zlib_output_stream.cc",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 54,
      "author": {
        "id": 1136770
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-08-17T01:50:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e The purpose of DCHECK(flushed) is to prevent caller from calling Write() but not Flush(), I actually should have bool alert_flush_not_called \u003d false, turn it on in Write() and turn it off in Flush, and dcheck it destructor.\n\u003e \n\u003e It seems not related to initialization, right?\n\nThis should conceptually decoupled from initialization. I was discussing initialization becauseb your DCHECK(initialized_.is_valid()) on this line, as you’ve written the code, mandates that Write() (which has Initialize() as a side effect, and being the only way for anything outside of the class to trigger Initialize()) be called before FLush().\n\nI understand what you’re using flushed_ for. The problem is that it’s impossible to use this class as you’ve written it by (1) allocating a ZlibOutputStream, (2) not calling Write() (for example, because there’s no data to write), and then (3) calling Flush(). I gave an example scenario detailing when that pattern might occur.\n\nAs far as flushed_ goes, my recommendation would be to switch it to flush_needed_. In the constructor, you’d set flush_needed_ \u003d false. Whenever Write() is called, you’d set it to true. In Flush(), you’d set it to false. And in the destructor, you’d DCHECK(!flush_needed_).",
      "parentUuid": "2f2b2fe7_f4752d9d",
      "revId": "7438e06f309a431d675c1b81e75fc31071f20d2b",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
